---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
export const prerender = true;
---
<Base title="robots.txt and AI Crawlers — Complete Guide (2025)" description="The definitive guide to robots.txt for AI crawlers. All known AI bot User-Agents, configuration patterns, testing guide, and best practices for 2025.">
  <article class="learn-page">
    <div class="container content">
      <nav class="breadcrumb" aria-label="Breadcrumb">
        <a href="/">Home</a> / <a href="/learn/robots-txt">Learn</a> / <span>robots.txt</span>
      </nav>

      <h1>robots.txt and AI Crawlers</h1>
      <p class="lead">
        <strong>robots.txt</strong> has been the standard for controlling web crawlers since 1994.
        With AI companies now sending dozens of bots to scrape the web for training data, it's your
        primary tool for controlling who gets access to your content.
      </p>

      <nav class="toc" aria-label="Table of contents">
        <h2 class="toc-title">On this page</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><a href="#how-it-works">How robots.txt works</a></li>
          <li><a href="#ai-crawlers">All known AI crawlers (2025)</a></li>
          <li><a href="#patterns">Configuration patterns</a></li>
          <li><a href="#training-vs-browsing">Training vs. browsing bots</a></li>
          <li><a href="#best-practices">Best practices</a></li>
          <li><a href="#testing">Testing your robots.txt</a></li>
          <li><a href="#comparison">Comparison with other files</a></li>
          <li><a href="#faq">FAQ</a></li>
        </ul>
      </nav>

      <section id="how-it-works">
        <h2>How robots.txt works</h2>
        <p>
          Place a file at <code>/robots.txt</code> on your domain root. It contains rules that tell
          crawlers which paths they're allowed or disallowed from accessing.
        </p>
        <pre><code>User-agent: *
Allow: /

User-agent: GPTBot
Disallow: /private/

Sitemap: https://example.com/sitemap.xml</code></pre>

        <h3>Key directives</h3>
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr><th>Directive</th><th>Purpose</th><th>Example</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td><code>User-agent</code></td><td>Which bot the rules apply to. <code>*</code> = all bots.</td><td><code>User-agent: GPTBot</code></td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>Allow</code></td><td>Explicitly permit access to a path</td><td><code>Allow: /docs/</code></td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>Disallow</code></td><td>Block access to a path</td><td><code>Disallow: /admin/</code></td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>Sitemap</code></td><td>Point crawlers to your sitemap</td><td><code>Sitemap: https://example.com/sitemap.xml</code></td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>Crawl-delay</code></td><td>Seconds between requests (not all bots honor this)</td><td><code>Crawl-delay: 10</code></td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>

        <h3>Rule precedence</h3>
        <p>When multiple rules match, the most specific one wins:</p>
        <ol>
          <li>Bot-specific rules override <code>User-agent: *</code></li>
          <li>Longer path patterns override shorter ones</li>
          <li><code>Allow</code> overrides <code>Disallow</code> when both match with equal specificity</li>
        </ol>
      </section>

      <section id="ai-crawlers">
        <h2>All known AI crawlers (2025)</h2>
        <p>This is the most comprehensive list of AI User-Agent strings. Updated regularly.</p>

        <h3>Training bots (scrape content for model training)</h3>
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr><th>Bot</th><th>Company</th><th>Notes</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td><code>GPTBot</code></td><td>OpenAI</td><td>Primary training crawler</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>Google-Extended</code></td><td>Google</td><td>AI training only (does NOT affect Google Search indexing)</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>anthropic-ai</code></td><td>Anthropic</td><td>Training data collection</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>Bytespider</code></td><td>ByteDance</td><td>Training for TikTok AI features</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>CCBot</code></td><td>Common Crawl</td><td>Open dataset used by many AI labs</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>cohere-ai</code></td><td>Cohere</td><td>Enterprise AI training</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>meta-externalagent</code></td><td>Meta</td><td>Training for Llama models</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>Diffbot</code></td><td>Diffbot</td><td>Web data extraction and knowledge graphs</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>Applebot-Extended</code></td><td>Apple</td><td>Training Apple Intelligence features</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>FacebookBot</code></td><td>Meta</td><td>AI feature training</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>omgili</code></td><td>Webz.io</td><td>Data collection for AI applications</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>Timpibot</code></td><td>Timpi</td><td>Decentralized search/AI</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>

        <h3>Browsing/search bots (real-time web access for AI features)</h3>
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr><th>Bot</th><th>Company</th><th>Notes</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td><code>ChatGPT-User</code></td><td>OpenAI</td><td>Live browsing in ChatGPT conversations</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>OAI-SearchBot</code></td><td>OpenAI</td><td>SearchGPT and search features</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>Claude-Web</code></td><td>Anthropic</td><td>Live web access in Claude conversations</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>PerplexityBot</code></td><td>Perplexity</td><td>AI-powered search engine</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>YouBot</code></td><td>You.com</td><td>AI search</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>Amazonbot</code></td><td>Amazon</td><td>Alexa and Amazon search AI</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>

        <div class="notice info">
          <strong>New bots appear regularly.</strong> The AI landscape changes fast. We update this list
          when new bots are documented. <a href="/">Scan your domain</a> to see which bots your current
          robots.txt covers.
        </div>
      </section>

      <section id="patterns">
        <h2>Configuration patterns</h2>

        <h3>Pattern 1: AI-friendly (allow everything)</h3>
        <p>Best for: sites that want maximum AI visibility (docs, open-source projects, content marketing).</p>
        <pre><code>User-agent: *
Allow: /

Sitemap: https://example.com/sitemap.xml</code></pre>

        <h3>Pattern 2: Block training, allow browsing</h3>
        <p>Best for: sites that want to appear in AI search results but don't want content used for training.</p>
        <pre><code># Block training bots
User-agent: GPTBot
Disallow: /

User-agent: Google-Extended
Disallow: /

User-agent: anthropic-ai
Disallow: /

User-agent: CCBot
Disallow: /

User-agent: Bytespider
Disallow: /

User-agent: cohere-ai
Disallow: /

User-agent: meta-externalagent
Disallow: /

# Allow browsing/search bots
User-agent: ChatGPT-User
Allow: /

User-agent: Claude-Web
Allow: /

User-agent: PerplexityBot
Allow: /

User-agent: OAI-SearchBot
Allow: /

# Allow traditional search
User-agent: Googlebot
Allow: /

User-agent: Bingbot
Allow: /

Sitemap: https://example.com/sitemap.xml</code></pre>

        <h3>Pattern 3: Selective access (protect premium content)</h3>
        <p>Best for: sites with both free and premium content.</p>
        <pre><code>User-agent: GPTBot
Allow: /blog/
Allow: /docs/
Disallow: /premium/
Disallow: /members/
Disallow: /api/internal/

User-agent: ChatGPT-User
Allow: /blog/
Allow: /docs/
Disallow: /premium/

Sitemap: https://example.com/sitemap.xml</code></pre>

        <h3>Pattern 4: Block all AI bots</h3>
        <p>Best for: sites that want zero AI interaction (paywalled news, proprietary content).</p>
        <pre><code>User-agent: GPTBot
Disallow: /

User-agent: ChatGPT-User
Disallow: /

User-agent: Google-Extended
Disallow: /

User-agent: anthropic-ai
Disallow: /

User-agent: Claude-Web
Disallow: /

User-agent: CCBot
Disallow: /

User-agent: PerplexityBot
Disallow: /

User-agent: Bytespider
Disallow: /

User-agent: cohere-ai
Disallow: /

User-agent: meta-externalagent
Disallow: /

User-agent: Applebot-Extended
Disallow: /

# Keep traditional search
User-agent: Googlebot
Allow: /

User-agent: Bingbot
Allow: /

Sitemap: https://example.com/sitemap.xml</code></pre>
      </section>

      <section id="training-vs-browsing">
        <h2>Training vs. browsing: a critical distinction</h2>
        <p>
          Not all AI bots do the same thing. Understanding the difference is key to making the right decision:
        </p>
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr><th></th><th>Training Bots</th><th>Browsing/Search Bots</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td><strong>What they do</strong></td><td>Scrape content to include in future model training data</td><td>Fetch pages in real-time to answer user queries</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>When they run</strong></td><td>Batch crawling (periodic)</td><td>On-demand (when a user asks about your site)</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Impact of blocking</strong></td><td>Your content won't be in future model training</td><td>AI can't cite or reference your site in real-time answers</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Recommendation</strong></td><td>Block if you don't want content used for training</td><td>Consider allowing, as it drives traffic like traditional search</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
        <p>
          <strong>The nuance:</strong> Blocking GPTBot (training) but allowing ChatGPT-User (browsing) means
          your content won't be baked into the model, but ChatGPT can still visit your site live when a user
          asks about you. This is the most common configuration for commercial sites.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section id="best-practices">
        <h2>Best practices</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Be explicit:</strong> Name specific bots rather than relying only on <code>User-agent: *</code>. AI bots may not respect wildcard rules as reliably as traditional search bots.</li>
          <li><strong>Review quarterly:</strong> New AI bots appear every few months. Check our <a href="#ai-crawlers">crawler list</a> and update your rules.</li>
          <li><strong>Include a Sitemap directive:</strong> Even if you block some bots, the Sitemap directive helps allowed crawlers discover your content efficiently.</li>
          <li><strong>Remember robots.txt is advisory:</strong> Well-behaved bots respect it. Malicious bots ignore it. It's a signal, not a firewall.</li>
          <li><strong>Don't block paths that are already public:</strong> If your docs are publicly accessible, blocking AI crawlers just means they'll get worse information about you, not no information.</li>
          <li><strong>Pair with ai.txt:</strong> robots.txt controls access. <a href="/learn/ai-txt">ai.txt</a> communicates policy. Use both for a complete AI governance approach.</li>
          <li><strong>Test before deploying:</strong> A misconfigured robots.txt can accidentally block legitimate search engines. Always test with multiple tools.</li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <section id="testing">
        <h2>Testing your robots.txt</h2>
        <p>Before deploying changes, verify your configuration:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Scan with our tool:</strong> <a href="/">Enter your domain</a> and we'll analyze which AI bots are allowed vs blocked.</li>
          <li><strong>Check syntax:</strong> Use <a href="https://developers.google.com/search/docs/crawling-indexing/robots/robots_txt" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Google's robots.txt tester</a> in Search Console.</li>
          <li><strong>Verify access:</strong> <code>curl -A "GPTBot" https://yoursite.com/robots.txt</code> to see what the bot sees.</li>
          <li><strong>Monitor:</strong> Check your server logs for AI bot User-Agents to see which bots are actually visiting.</li>
        </ol>

        <h3>Quick curl test</h3>
        <pre><code># Check what GPTBot sees
curl -A "GPTBot" https://yoursite.com/

# Verify robots.txt is accessible
curl https://yoursite.com/robots.txt

# Check with our API
curl "https://llmstxt.codes/api/v1/scan?domain=yoursite.com" | jq .subScores.robotsTxt</code></pre>
      </section>

      <section id="comparison">
        <h2>robots.txt vs. other AI files</h2>
        <p>
          robots.txt controls <em>access</em>. It says "you may or may not crawl." But it doesn't
          tell AI what your site is about (<a href="/learn/llms-txt">llms.txt</a>) or set usage policies
          (<a href="/learn/ai-txt">ai.txt</a>). A complete AI strategy uses all three.
        </p>
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr><th>Question</th><th>Answer</th><th>File</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Can this bot crawl my site?</td><td>Access control</td><td><code>robots.txt</code></td></tr>
            <tr><td>What is my site about?</td><td>Context for AI</td><td><code>llms.txt</code></td></tr>
            <tr><td>Can AI companies use my content?</td><td>Usage policy</td><td><code>ai.txt</code></td></tr>
            <tr><td>What pages exist on my site?</td><td>Page discovery</td><td><code>sitemap.xml</code></td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </section>

      <section id="faq">
        <h2>FAQ</h2>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>Does blocking GPTBot also block ChatGPT?</h3>
          <p>
            No. GPTBot is used for training data collection. ChatGPT-User is a separate bot used
            for live browsing. You can block one without blocking the other.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>Does blocking Google-Extended affect my Google Search ranking?</h3>
          <p>
            No. Google-Extended only controls AI training (Gemini, Bard). Googlebot handles Search
            indexing separately. Blocking Google-Extended has zero impact on your search rankings.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>Will AI companies respect my robots.txt?</h3>
          <p>
            Major companies (OpenAI, Google, Anthropic, Meta) have publicly committed to respecting
            robots.txt. Smaller or less scrupulous operators may not. robots.txt is advisory, not
            enforceable. For legal protection, pair it with <a href="/learn/ai-txt">ai.txt</a>
            and explicit Terms of Service.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>Can I rate-limit AI bots instead of blocking them?</h3>
          <p>
            The <code>Crawl-delay</code> directive theoretically limits request frequency, but not
            all AI bots honor it. For reliable rate limiting, use server-side controls (Cloudflare
            Bot Management, nginx rate limiting, etc.).
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>My robots.txt already has rules but our scanner says I need improvement. Why?</h3>
          <p>
            We score based on explicit AI bot coverage. A generic <code>User-agent: * / Allow: /</code>
            gets a lower score than explicitly naming and configuring each AI bot. The more bots you
            explicitly address, the higher your score, because it shows intentional AI management.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <div class="cta-box">
        <h3>Check your robots.txt</h3>
        <p>See which AI bots your robots.txt allows or blocks, and what's missing.</p>
        <a href="/" class="action-btn action-btn-primary">Scan your domain</a>
        <a href="/tools/generator/robots-txt" class="action-btn action-btn-secondary">Generate robots.txt</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>
</Base>

<style>
  .learn-page { padding: var(--space-8) 0 var(--space-16); }
  .content { max-width: var(--content-width); }
  .breadcrumb { font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--color-text-muted); margin-bottom: var(--space-6); }
  .breadcrumb a { color: var(--color-text-secondary); }

  h1 { font-size: var(--text-3xl); font-weight: 700; margin-bottom: var(--space-4); }
  .lead { font-size: var(--text-lg); color: var(--color-text-secondary); line-height: var(--leading-relaxed); margin-bottom: var(--space-8); }

  h2 { font-size: var(--text-xl); font-weight: 600; margin-top: var(--space-10); margin-bottom: var(--space-4); }
  h3 { font-size: var(--text-lg); font-weight: 600; margin-top: var(--space-6); margin-bottom: var(--space-3); }

  section { margin-bottom: var(--space-8); }
  p { line-height: var(--leading-relaxed); margin-bottom: var(--space-3); }
  ul, ol { padding-left: var(--space-6); margin-bottom: var(--space-4); }
  li { margin-bottom: var(--space-2); line-height: var(--leading-relaxed); }

  code { font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: 0.9em; background: var(--color-bg); padding: 1px 4px; border-radius: var(--radius-sm); }
  pre { background: var(--color-surface); border: 1px solid var(--color-border); border-radius: var(--radius-md); padding: var(--space-4); overflow-x: auto; margin: var(--space-4) 0; }
  pre code { background: none; padding: 0; font-size: var(--text-sm); line-height: 1.6; }

  table { width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin: var(--space-4) 0; }
  th, td { padding: var(--space-3); text-align: left; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-border); }
  th { font-weight: 600; font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--color-text-secondary); }
  td { font-size: var(--text-sm); }

  /* Table of contents */
  .toc { background: var(--color-surface); border: 1px solid var(--color-border); border-radius: var(--radius-md); padding: var(--space-4) var(--space-6); margin-bottom: var(--space-8); }
  .toc-title { font-size: var(--text-sm); font-weight: 600; color: var(--color-text-secondary); text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.05em; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: var(--space-2); }
  .toc ul { columns: 2; padding-left: var(--space-4); margin: 0; }
  .toc li { font-size: var(--text-sm); margin-bottom: var(--space-1); }
  .toc a { color: var(--color-primary); text-decoration: none; }
  .toc a:hover { text-decoration: underline; }

  .notice { border-radius: var(--radius-md); padding: var(--space-4); margin: var(--space-4) 0; font-size: var(--text-sm); }
  .notice.info { background: #eff6ff; border: 1px solid #93c5fd; }
  .notice a { color: var(--color-primary); }

  /* FAQ */
  .faq-item { margin-bottom: var(--space-6); padding-bottom: var(--space-6); border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-border); }
  .faq-item:last-child { border-bottom: none; }
  .faq-item h3 { margin-top: 0; }
  .faq-item p { font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--color-text-secondary); }
  .faq-item a { color: var(--color-primary); }

  .cta-box {
    margin-top: var(--space-12); padding: var(--space-8); background: var(--color-primary-light);
    border-radius: var(--radius-lg); text-align: center;
  }
  .cta-box h3 { margin-top: 0; }
  .cta-box p { color: var(--color-text-secondary); margin-bottom: var(--space-4); }
  .cta-box :global(.action-btn) { margin: 0 var(--space-2); display: inline-block; }
  :global(.action-btn) { padding: var(--space-3) var(--space-6); border-radius: var(--radius-md); font-size: var(--text-sm); font-weight: 600; font-family: var(--font-sans); cursor: pointer; text-decoration: none; border: none; transition: background 0.15s; }
  :global(.action-btn-primary) { background: var(--color-primary); color: white; }
  :global(.action-btn-primary:hover) { background: var(--color-primary-hover); text-decoration: none; }
  :global(.action-btn-secondary) { background: var(--color-surface); color: var(--color-text); border: 1px solid var(--color-border); }
  :global(.action-btn-secondary:hover) { background: var(--color-bg); }

  @media (max-width: 640px) {
    .toc ul { columns: 1; }
  }
</style>
